::Okay, so think of it like this: You ha (e057a108-f587-488b-886b-93ca4ccb6a2f)

::Okay, so think of it like this: You have 3 blocks of 12 notes, each of the 36 corresponding to a letter of the alphabet (26 notes out of total 36, as I've mentioned before) and the other 10 are numbers, aligned so that the alphabet goes first, then the numbers. For example, the default arrangement is that letter *A* corresponds to note C, letter *B* to C#/Db, *C* to D, etc. Then the notes start repeating once you reach the letter M, so now letter *M* is note C, *N* is C#, etc. And you go all the way until you're done with the numbers as well.::
::So that's the basic setup. Now, the fi (3d89d1d3-35a2-48c2-9857-93546372bcaa)

::So that's the basic setup. Now, the first thing I do to manipulate this arrangement is to *transpose* the notes in all of these three blocks by a randomly selected interval. Let's say the first block is being transposed by a minor third (3 semitones, in keeping with the musical theme). That means that letter *A* now corresponds to note D#/Eb, letter *B* to E, *C* to F, etc. The same applies to the other two blocks.

However, the other two blocks are not only being transposed but also *modulated*; more precisely, since they have already been offset by the *transposition* interval (minor third), on top of that go the *modulation* intervals for each block.::

::Thadious

Interval key: major seventh, major third, major seventh.

Octave keys: 

Key 1: 63047444447474774544
Key 2: 63074764444777447456745
Key 3: 6304744644477
Key 4: 630444646444774764644
::
::For the second block let's pick anothe (076ee93b-bc04-48b4-9f5c-2372e7e1a985)

::For the second block let's pick another minor third, which makes that 6 semitones in total (*3*+3); 6 semitones from C is F#. So, again, the first block is offset *only* by the transposition interval, but once we reach the second we have *transposition* plus *first modulation*, so we start at the F# note. Now, the letter *M* (first letter of the second block) is F#, *N* is G, *O* is G#/Ab... The same principle applies to the third block: If the *second modulation* (offset interval for the third block) is a fifth (7 semitones above; *3* + 7 = 10; 10 semitones from C is A#/Bb), then letter *Y* (first letter of the third block) is A#/Bb, *Z* is B, (now we're starting with numbers) number *0* is C, *1* is C#/Db, etc.::

::These three musical intervals (transposition, first modulation and second modulation) compose the *interval* key used to decode the cipher. Next up are the octaves, because how will one know which of the three F's correspond to which letters/numbers?

Each block has its own starting octave, and octave numbers always start at the C note. If we, say, transpose a piece starting at B1 (the last note in the first octave) by a perfect fifth higher (7 semitones) then the next 7 notes belong to the higher octave (C2, C#2, D2, D#2, E2, F2 and F#2). In this case, our transposed piece now starts with F#2. The most important thing to remember is that octaves start with the C note, therefore the octave number will always become one higher every time we reach the next C.::

::Yusuf

Interval key: minor third, diminished fift?, major seventh.

Octave keys:

Key 1: 0363013433030400443330
Key 2: 03603343303000434443
Key 3: 0361000434340430300004040
Key 4: 036004333?41004030::
::The starting octaves for each of the t (6d676acc-b5f5-43a5-9b97-869a26e83aac)

::The starting octaves for each of the three blocks is something I generate, and that is the first part of the *octave* key. It's a three-digit number; first digit is the octave number for the first block, second digit for the second block, third digit for the third block. What's left now to do is encode the text (which in this instance were titles of works of our beloved composers) but keep the notes and their corresponding octave numbers separate. The notes are your encoded text, the octave numbers are the second part of your octave key. So your completed octave key is the three aforementioned starting octaves followed by all of these octave numbers. 

And that's all there is to it. What do you think?::
